Dear Governor Perdue,

I am writing to express my concern about an issue that was brought to my attention this week. It is about the More at four program being cut. It came as a shock actually to me, because just last week I was calling the news station and More at four headquarters to see how we could have my daughters Pre K teachers recognized for the hard work this year. So I take this chance as an opportunity to let you know that it would really be awful to loose such a great program for our children, our future generation. My daughter is the oldest of two in our family. My husband is military and I am an Air Force Veteran as of 2007. I got out of the service to stay at home with my children due to the dedication that is required of two military married members, and I decided my girls needed at least one steady parent always around. (Deployments happen all the time as you may already know) My daughter just turned 3 when I got out and I loved staying home with her. I took time during the day and worked with her on her alphabet, numbers, writing....etc. I literally got to the point where she was not staying interested in what I was teaching her because she was learning everything so well. Before she turned 4 I looked outside the home for help since as her parent I was struggling to keep her going, because I was running out of creative ways to teach her new things. I really felt she new everything! I learned about the more at four program and was so excited because she would be with teachers who have learned and know how to advance our children. Of course I was nervous of letting her go to a public school, and at orientation I was the parent who brought a list of questions to the teachers. I was worried about how they discipline, encourage, what they should know by now, and how much they involve us parents. Her teachers Mrs. Reid and Mrs. Presson were very warming to me as a mother and after my daughters first week in school I was at ease. These teachers are WONDERFUL!!! I had heard horror stories of how you have to literally make your presence known, or take the teachers disciplining your child, but I have not once ran into a problem. Her teachers talk to me everyday and I am always welcome in the class. Sometimes I will just show up just to see what they are learning and she is so happy there. They treat her and the others like they are their own children and these two women have so much patience. One thing that the teachers asked me at an initial home visit at the beginning of the year was "What is something Olivia needs to do well?" I said encouragement. We always acknowledge her when she does good and encourage her with everything. They really did listen to me, because Olivia will come home and tell me that Mrs. Reid or Mrs. Presson said she was a great listener today so she got to be the leader and hold the door open. Sometimes I will volunteer in the class and there are one or two kids with special needs and these teachers get hit, screamed at, and they respond with a gentle voice that calms the kids down. I personally don't know how they do it. I am not the only parent who feels this way about our teachers and we want to recognize them for their accomplishments.
     I think the best part of the year was when my four year old came home telling me what a compound word was. My husband and I were very impressed and we called our families in SC, and VA to let them hear her. I didn't learn compound words until after kindergarten, so that goes to show they really do work with our children. They have instilled a love for school in my daughter and have taught me ways to continue with her learning at home. Since she is my oldest I ask for help on ways to improve anything she needs with education and these teachers are more than willing to teach me. My daughter has even taught me a few things from this program. They have something the teacher does and it's called "kiss your brain" and they will kiss their first two fingers and tap their head when they say something correct. It's something we have welcomed in our house and my youngest daughter learns from her as well.  I was given a paper about a reading program from her teachers and I went to sign my daughter up and she is already on a first grade reading level! I couldn't put her in the program but I did ask her teachers to help me with some stuff over the summer so she stays on top of things. Her teachers automatically helped me and gave me great ideas. I have one of the teachers on speed dial and she will take my call at anytime of the day. They have taught our kids how to talk things out with their friends, and my daughter refers to everyone as a friend. Please don't get rid of this program. It is so important that our children learn early in life because technology and knowledge in general is very important to succeed in life. I truly feel my daughter Olivia has received a great step in the education system, and she has a 3 year old sister who I want to be able to have the same chance. If  I didn't put Olivia in the program she would not be on  the level she is now, because I didn't know what steps to take next. Even if you decide to keep more at four, but make it not free this would still hurt people. As I mentioned before we are a military family and we still struggle financially, and I don't want my children to miss out on any opportunity to excel in life because of our shortcomings. We already deal with deployments, and the economy, and every day struggles. Education is so important and should be extended to every child. On a different note, I know that there are parents that do take advantage of having their child in the care of another person. We have experienced it at our school, but these teachers look at every child as their own person. A parents shortcomings should not affect the future of a child. There are other parents who will always step up and help the teachers when needed and these children need this. Please again don't do away with this program. If you could only visit Tommy's Road Elementary school for one day you would see the positive impact Mrs. Reid and Mrs. Presson have on our innocent children. Thanks for your time. If you need to reach me I can be reached at this email or my phone at (919) 221-4321. My daughters school is Tommy's Road Elementary in Goldsboro.

Sincerely,
Melissa Holt

