Dear Governor Perdue,

I am a Pre-K teacher in the More @4 program in one of the NC public schools.  I have recently read the proposed legislation and budget cuts for the upcoming year.  I must say as a parent of a pre-schooler and a public educator that I disagree with the cuts to the youngest student population.  This program has helped countless students enter Kindergarten ready to learn.  Cutting the funding will cause us to limit this service to the poverty level community that we serve.  It will also mean that students who need to be screened and identified for Exceptional Children's services will slip through the cracks.

I have been in education for almost 10 years now.  I used to teach 1st grade lower level students.  I saw the struggles that some children made daily.  I knew that they could have done better only if someone had intervened sooner.  The first years of a child's life are the most impressionable ones of their lives.  This is when they can easily learn a second language, make friends that look and act differently than just their family, and lay a foundation that will prepare them to receive an education and enter society as a productive citizen.  


Our pre-K program doesn't prepare these children by teaching them their ABC's, 123's, shapes and colors.  Our program takes students from at risk homes and encourages them to learn a better way.  We teach students how to respect teachers, students and administrators.  They learn how to follow a routine and classroom discipline so that Kindergarten is not emotionally and academically overwhelming.  They start out learning that education is fun, exciting, and useful.  Their parents are involved in education workshops, parent conferences, and school events.  They are proud to see their child(ren)growing in knowledge because they know that it will lead to a brighter future for them and America.

You may not see the results just yet because this program has only been in existence for the past decade.  Some of the first students have not had the opportunity to graduate from High School yet.  I do think that our program is helping K-2 teachers get students who are ready to learn and in turn is able to produce better readers and problem solvers.  Who then move on to the 3-5 teachers that can take these independent learners to the next level and teach to the individual student's needs. This also allows the state's EOG test scores to rise.  As these students continue on through to the 12th grade, they begin to focus on a trade/job or a college education.  Both of which have been the strength in America's work force throughout the 20th century.

Now that we are in the 21st century, the economic tide has turned.  If the cuts that you are suggesting go through, then I feel as though the state has not valued my work as an educator and that my efforts have been in vain.  I love my job and I love my student's as though they were my own.  I have spent countless dollars of coins that I have thrown in a jar on little extras that bring my lessons to life.  I am already struggling with my own family.  I am the sole income of the household.  My husband lost his job in December.  I have three children, one of which has Sensory Processing Disorder and ADHD.  Even on a teacher's salary, we qualify for NC health choice.  Times are tough for everyone.

North Carolina has been my home since birth.  I am proud to have attended the Nation's top school of education at Greensboro College.  I am happy to see the progress that we are making in public education at the early stages.  I am simply asking that you seriously consider budget cuts at some other places rather than the pre-k programs.  My colleagues and I can see the need to not open any new classrooms just yet; nonetheless, are these drastic cuts to our end of the system necessary?  Let's hold tight to what we have and continue to strengthen our educational system so that we can have citizens that can work for America in the future. 

I know that you have to make a tough decision.  Thank you for taking time to consider my concerns as both a citizen and an employee of North Carolina.  I pray you will make wise decisions about my family's future.

Sincerely,

Michelle A. Tuttle
Walter Bickett Education Center
Monroe, NC

